<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIVE INSURANCE CONSUMERS AN ADVOCATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RALPH NADER, Ralph Nader is a consumer advocate and founder of the 
Washington-based Center for Responsive Law. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie has finally begun hearings to determine 
whether individual insurers should be required to roll back their rates as 
directed by Proposition 103. These hearings will also determine the size of the 
refund checks that consumers will receive from insurers for excess premiums 
charged during the past year. 
</P>
<P>
In evaluating insurers' petitions for exemptions from the rollbacks, Gillespie 
will hear abundant assertions from legions of lawyers and actuaries working for 
the insurance companies. But she will hear little from insurance experts for 
consumers. That's because consumers lack their own team of actuaries and 
lawyers to scrutinize the thousand-plus exemption petitions. Instead, consumers 
will have little recourse but to cross their fingers in the largely vain hope 
that Gillespie, a former insurance-company executive, will act in good faith to 
implement the Proposition 103 rollbacks. 
</P>
<P>
It doesn't have to be this way. The authors of Proposition 103 knew full well 
that consumers would have to be empowered to safeguard the initiative from 
subversion by the industry and its official allies. So when they drafted the 
measure, they included a provision to establish an independent consumer 
insurance organization staffed by insurance experts to intervene on behalf of 
consumers in regulatory proceedings before the commissioner. This is exactly 
what consumers need. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the California Supreme Court ruled that such a provision 
technically violated a state institutional prohibition against naming a private 
corporation in a ballot initiative. But the court did made it clear that the 
Legislature was free to pass a law creating the rate-payer organization. 
</P>
<P>
Shortly thereafter, Senate President David A. Roberti (D-Los Angeles) 
introduced such legislation. Taken verbatim from Proposition 103, the Roberti 
bill has been approved by the Senate but faces an uncertain fate in the 
Assembly Finance and Insurance Committee, where a vote has been scheduled for 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
While the measure has thus far received scant attention from the media, it is 
the most innovative consumer protection legislation given serious consideration 
by the Legislature in years. If enacted, California policyholders will be the 
first consumers in the country to have an institutional, yet independent, role 
in their state's insurance rate-review process. 
</P>
<P>
Here is how it would work: Whenever an insurance company mails out its bills, 
it would be required to enclose a notice inviting policyholders to join an 
organization that would fight for their rights and interests before the 
Insurance Department, the courts and the Legislature. After voluntarily paying 
a modest membership fee, member policyholders would elect a board that would 
then hire a staff of professional insurance experts. Because these experts 
would be accountable to consumers only, there would be no danger they would be 
co-opted by special interests (as frequently happens with government consumer 
protection agencies). In addition, the Consumer Insurance Organization would 
involve no expenditure of taxpayer money, nor any out-of-pocket expense for 
insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
While those legislators who front for the insurance industry argue that 
consumers are already well enough represented by existing consumer groups, they 
know full well that on the regulatory battlefield these groups are badly 
outnumbered by an infinitely larger and wealthier insurance industry. The fact 
is that the half-dozen or so consumer groups in California that are active on 
insurance issues simply do not have the staff or technical capability to 
challenge more than a few of the thousands of exemption petitions and rate 
filings that the commissioner will rule on over the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
After being trounced by consumers at the polls last fall, insurers must find it 
very comforting indeed to know that when it comes to implementing the rollbacks 
and rate regulation ordered by Proposition 103, consumers have their hands tied 
behind their backs. For the industry, the next few months of hearings before 
the Insurance Department represent an opportunity to seize the power to 
determine prices that it lost to the voters last November. 
</P>
<P>
For consumers, the inevitable domination of the upcoming hearings by 
insurance-industry lawyers represents a serious threat to their victory last 
fall. Like other consumer protection measures, Proposition 103 is an instrument 
rather than a result. Unless it is applied aggressively and by government 
officials who are serving their rightful masters, it will not produce the 
intended result. And the only way for consumers to make sure that officials 
such as Gillespie act in the public interest is to be there, watching over her 
shoulder every step of the way. 
</P>
<P>
After being written off by insurance consumers as cowards, the Legislature has 
unexpectedly been given an opportunity by the state Supreme Court to join with 
consumers in standing up to the industry and ensuring that Proposition 103 
works for consumers. The Legislature must seize this opportunity by passing the 
Roberti bill to establish the Consumer Insurance Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
