<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 SOUTHLAND BUSINESSMEN TO BUY LIQUOR BARN CHAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JESUS SANCHEZ, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two San Diego area businessmen on Wednesday said they have agreed to buy the 
68-store Liquor Barn chain, which filed for bankruptcy protection last year. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement to acquire the assets of the San Leandro, Calif.-based chain must 
still be approved by Liquor Barn's creditors and the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in 
Oakland. No purchase price was disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
The buyers, Lewis Silverberg, a San Diego attorney, and Harvey W. Rosen of 
Rancho Santa Fe, said in a statement that they were seeking an equity partner. 
Silverberg and Rosen were not available for further comment. Liquor Barn 
President John Thompson was also not available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Financial Problems 
</P>
<P>
A former Safeway Stores subsidiary, Liquor Barn grew into a 104-store chain 
with $332 million in sales on a no-frills, discount-price strategy. But the 
chain's financial troubles began after Safeway sold the chain in 1987 to 
London-based Majestic Wine, a small British wine retailer. Majestic hoped to 
boost sales by replacing Liquor Barn's discount image with an upscale wine 
merchant approach. Employees were trained to advise customers on wine 
selection, and periodic wine tastings were planned. 
</P>
<P>
But the plan backfired as old customers stayed away and the new, upscale 
shoppers never materialized. Industry analysts also said Majestic may have paid 
too much -- an estimated $110 million -- for a chain that never turned a 
profit. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Lost Control of Firm 
</P>
<P>
Majestic reversed its policy but was unable to attract former customers. Last 
year, Majestic lost control of Liquor Barn to American and British bankers who 
acquired 66% of the chain. 
</P>
<P>
A company turnaround would be both expensive and difficult, say industry 
observers. 
</P>
<P>
"They must try and regain the image and identity they had originally," said Max 
Kerstein, publisher of Beverage Bulletin. "They are going to have to compete 
against the heavyweights, like Price Club, that have taken the play away from 
them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LIQUOR BARN LTD; ACQUISITIONS; SILVERBERG, LEWIS; ROSEN, HARVEY W; DISCOUNT 
STORES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
