<P>
GENDARMES WARNED TO HALT PROTEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government warned today that it will stamp out an unprecedented protest 
movement among France's gendarmes, the paramilitary police renowned for their 
stiff-backed devotion to duty. 
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said the protests over poor conditions 
in the 91,000-member force have gone too far and are politically orchestrated. 
</P>
<P>
"Anonymous appeals are even inciting gendarmes, the guardians of legality, to 
take illegal action," Chevenement said in an open letter to all ranks. "This is 
not acceptable and will not be accepted." 
</P>
<P>
After years of grumbling in vain about low pay, long hours and the martial 
bleakness of barrack life, gendarmes spread the spirit of rebellion rapidly 
this week. In a cascade of anonymous letters to newspapers, gendarmes 
throughout France have risked dismissal by threatening to stage the first 
industrial action in the gendarmerie's centuries of history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
